Parallel: Evaluating the PRIME Thesis
Kel

Dec 14, 2023 ⋅  10 min read

Key Insights

  • Parallel has drawn interest from championship Web2 gamers and crypto-native investors as the crypto gaming thesis begins to make a comeback.
  • The Parallel ecosystem is comprised of a trading card battling game and Colony, an AI-Agent assisted multiplayer game.
  • The Colony game has potential to expand the addressable player base and token buying pressure by allowing users to delegate gameplay to autonomous agents with emergent, expressive character traits.
  • Our most optimistic assumption forecasts that baseline – that is, the bare necessity – gameplay costs could catalyze 4% of the PRIME token supply in buying pressure from legitimate users.
  • Risks to adoption include distribution, scale, and economic challenges that have all yet to be tested at scale.

Parallel is potentially poised to bridge the gap between Web2 and Web3 gamers. On one end, their new AI-Agent-enabled game, Colony, has the potential to birth a net-new gamer userbase by unlocking collaboration with expressive AI Avatars with a story of their own to tell. On the other end, their trading card game – still in closed beta – has already sparked considerable interest from world champion gamers, blue chip investors, and speculators alike.

Both games are targeting 6-7-figure MAU markets that print hundreds of millions in revenue for several existing games today.

In turn, with the potential success of these games come the potential for large buy pressure on the PRIME token – as it serves as the sole entrypoint into the heart of the Parallel ecosystem.

Parallel aims to set itself apart with a blend of key differentiators, including:

  • Unique gameplay mechanics & Net-new game modes
  • Improved economic design
  • Emphasis on lore and graphic design

When combined with derisked user experience issues that plagued previous gaming cycles in the crypto space, the case for Parallel is compelling. Before delving deeper into its nuances and potential impact, it's crucial to understand what Parallel truly is and what sets it apart in the crypto application landscape.

Parallel Overview

Parallel is made up of two core components – a trading card game (TCG) and Colony, their AI-agent enabled multiplayer game. Such games don’t sound as promising as a DeFi protocol or a new L1, but let’s establish some context first before you decide what to think on gaming.

Source: NY Times

Successful trading card games print money. Games like Magic: The Gathering have 5+ million monthly active user counts who collectively funnel hundreds of millions in yearly revenues into their platforms, and that’s only considering online gameplay. All that is without any cryptonomic incentives, circular speculation, or any of the other mechanisms a large percentage of crypto projects rely on to get anywhere close to similar numbers.

On the AI side, the best available comparable we have would be massively multiplayer online games. Games like World of Warcraft have millions of DAUs generating 100s of millions in revenue for parent company Activision. Parallel’s colony looks to, in the endgame, somewhat replicate that model while simultaneously expanding the userbase by allowing for semi-active players to “play” the game through their agent when the human player is away.

As a result, competitor projects like Parallel should be taken seriously.

TCG overview

The basic premise of any trading card game is that users compile decks of cards that battle against other users. Typically, each “team” has an amount of “health points” (HP) – whichever team goes to zero first loses. There’s a ton more nuance to the gameplay within the Parallel TCG – beginner guides, info on maximizing PRIME earnings, and a lot more. Bogging down into those details isn’t necessary here. All that we need to know is that players have both a free to play option and NFT-based gaming.

Free to play players don’t have to buy in to gain access to the game, but also don’t receive PRIME rewards for playing and winning games. NFT-based players build a minimum of 40 card decks that allow them to win PRIME rewards for playing and winning matches. Rewards are scaled to competition level, giving players an incentive to climb the rankings as high as they can in order to win the maximum amount possible.

Colony overview

Colony is Parallel’s experimental AI Agent game. What the endstate here looks like is uncertain, but it’s probably best analogized to a massively multiplayer online game, or MMO. In these, hundreds or even thousands of players collaborate and compete on various quests with a wide range of objectives, with the end goal being resource, status, and skill accumulation. The canonical example is World of Warcraft, which printed $700m+ in revenue for parent company Activision off of anywhere from 2-5m DAU in 2022.

MMO explainer aside, Colony’s unique edge here is the AI element. Instead of players spending 10+ hours playing these multiplayer games themselves, the idea is that player-semi-controlled AI Avatars would do the lion’s share of the resource competing and multiplayer interactions. Players would load their agents up with PRIME tokens and also receive PRIME based off of the success or failure of their Avatars in the pursuit of those resources.

The Colony game mode in particular has promise as a new way for gamers to interact with one another through the medium of AI.

For gamers, AI-enhanced gameplay could expand market size as MMO-type gamers can enjoy multiplayer content without having to devote 8 hours a day towards grinding away at, well, everything. By delegating that grind to semi-autonomous agents, the total “play time” can go up massively as the demographic of people who have any semblance of time outside of gaming can now have their agent game for them for some portion of the time.

This is different from traditional non-playable characters in gaming due to the expressive, emergent characteristics of AI Agents. Few people are excited to see predictable CPUs duke it out in a resource war that plays out similarly every time. The jury’s still out on whether or not people will do that for expressive AIs in Colony, but the case there is far more palpable. I would love to see an AI modeled after my style battle against my friends’ AIs.

For the Parallel economy, the adoption of agents provides an avenue towards increased “GDP” because unlike people, who have to step away from the games to tend to the kids, AI agents can play the game forever with limited resource constrictions. This could also lead to increased user spending, as while humans undergo some level of decision weighting analysis when it comes to marginal purchases of ingame assets, AIs trained for resource maximization likely face no such decision paralysis.

In sum, more players, spending more per player.

Evaluating The PRIME Token Economy

In play-to earn gaming, there’s a difficult balance to strike between issuance and removal of tokens on and off the market. For example, Eve Online, another successful MMO, regularly puts out very granular reports on the status of their economy. EVE has a very robust system of currency sinks and faucets, yet their ingame currency ISK has still gone through multiple periods of hyperinflation.

Source: Eve Online Monthly Report

Parallel’s ability to manage PRIME sinks and faucets and avoid hyperinflation will be integral to the game’s success. The team seems well aware of this need, reporting that their closed beta has captured ~5% of the circulating supply into token sinks as of November 27th.

Source: Echelon Docs

Additionally, the team just released Sanctuary, their own native marketplace for the PRIME ecosystem. As the EVE online graphic above shows, transaction taxes are often the #1 sink for in game economies at any level of scale. Leaking those taxes to third party marketplaces isn’t feasible for any game in the long run – it’s part of the reason we highlighted the Unbundling of Opensea thesis during August of 2022.

Rather than just burning tokens, which would have appeal from a pseudo-token-revenue point of view, PRIME tokens captured in token sinks are funneled back into the Parallel ecosystem to fund future growth. This method takes tokens off the market in a similar fashion to burning them, but also allows for potentially self-sustaining growth as sink tokens are kept in reserve to pay for growth years down the line.

Source: Echelon Documentation

While the vast majority of tokens are allocated towards funding future gameplay growth, there are also allocations to the Echelon foundation (team), Prime Drives (luxury NFT), and Parasets (specific card sets). These allocations are small but serve to incentivize both the team as well as expensive card collectors.

As the Parallel ecosystem expands, our relatively conservative estimates could see up to 4% of the total – not circulating – token supply sunk by players.

Given gaming’s past failures, it may seem farfetched to project 100 thousand users on any timeframe, let alone 1 million. However, there are a number of MMOs and trading card games without any incentive accelerants that put up 100k+ user numbers.

Spending offers a further avenue for buy pressure growth. The above is only taking into consideration the base level necessities players would need just to enter into the game, without taking cosmetic purchases, card hoarding, and more into account. Given the $50 billion size of the gaming market, and the (albeit anecdotal) tendency for players to hoard cards well beyond the base level necessity needed, it’s feasible to expect player buy pressure to be significantly higher than where it is here. For reference, Parallel has already done 80k+ ETH in volume on their trading cards, most of which was driven by speculative demand from the 2021 era, well before the game went live.

Moreover, prices could be adjusted higher than what’s shown above – for example the Avatars which power Colony are trading at ~20x the initial PRIME mint cost used above (although it doesn’t seem like the best strategy for costs to be so prohibitive).  Lastly, this doesn't forecast the amount of PRIME users will delegate to their AI avatars to utilize within Colony.

Challenges To Adoption

The above picture may be pretty, but there’s a number of challenges to overcome on the road to adoption:

Distribution challenges: Crypto games have yet to properly crack distribution. That’s changing to a degree with the Epic Games store (which Parallel is in) becoming more amicable to crypto as well as easier mobile integrations via embedded wallets and other new application interfaces. Still, until any of these hit at scale, the jury is out.

Scalability: Parallel is currently on ETH L1 and supports a card mirroring system that allows issuance of cards onto L2s called Echoes. That said, neither option seems really ready for 100k+ concurrent user scale, which may be one reason why the Parallel founder has displayed interest in talking with the Solana team in a now-deleted tweet.

Inflation Risks: Even with token sinks across several gamemodes, inflationary pressure from mercenary game farmers playing for and subsequently dumponig tokens is always a latent risk for any crypto game.

Conclusion

Parallel has multiple narrative and mechanical tailwinds that could propel its ecosystem into legitimate web2 level scale. While the PRIME token is up significantly throughout 2023, it still might offer venture scale returns with other crypto gaming projects and successful web2 games all trading at multiples of PRIME’s current valuation.

Whether or not PRIME flips its comparables is a question I can’t answer, but the project is certainly one to watch as we start the new year.
